## Events

Whenever a user has typed something on their keyboard, or moved their mouse, Java fires off an event. It captures information about the event in a special event object. For example, which key was being pressed. It then passes this event object to some event listeners. We can define an event listener to "listen" to these events, performing some action.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

For example, when the user moves their mouse, Java will generate a `MouseEvent`. If we define a `MouseListener` and attach it to a program, we can get these `MouseEvents`. Lets take a look at this concept in practice. 

## KeyAdapters

Java defines a KeyAdapter class that allows us to listen to events. 

> KeyAdapter is an abstract class which implements the KeyListener interface. We prefer to extend KeyAdapter as opposed to implementing KeyListener because KeyAdapter already defines all of the required methods in the KeyListener interface. We can simply override the ones we need. On the other hand, implementing KeyListener would mean implementing all of the methods in the interface contract.

We extend this class in our `GameState`. 

```java
public class GameState extends KeyAdapter {
```
*GameState.java*

We can then override a method to start listening to key events!

> Overriding a method gives it a new behavior. By default, the `KeyAdapter` class does nothing on all keyboard events. If we override a method, we can add a new behavior, such as printing out the character that got typed, or moving a character across the screen.

```java
  @Override
  public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
    System.out.println(e.getKeyChar());
  }
```
*GameState.java*

The `@Override` tag simply tells the constructor that we are overriding a method. This is useful in double checking that you didn't misspell anything.

Now that we've defined a KeyAdapter, we have to tell Java that we want it to be listening for events. We can do this with the `.addKeyListener` method on `JFrame`. 

```java
    frame.addKeyListener(state);
```
*Main.java*

You should notice that when we press a button on your keyboard, that letter shows up in the console!

## KeyEvents

KeyEvents are passed in through the `keyPressed` method, and describe all the information related to a user's key press. The most useful method is probably be `getKeyChar`, which returns the character that got pressed. For example.

```java
  @Override
  public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
    char c = e.getKeyChar();
    System.out.println("The character you pressed was " + c);
  }
```

You can then take this character, and use it to determine what action to take next. This could be done with if statements, or a switch statement. 

```java
    char c = e.getKeyChar();

    if (c == 'w') {

    } else if (c == 'a') {

    } else if (c == 's') {

    } else if (c == 'd') {

    }
```
*if statements*

```java
    char c = e.getKeyChar();

    switch (c) {
    case 'w':
      break;         
    case 'a':
      break;
    case 's':
      break;
    case 'd':
      break;
    }
```
*switch statements*

Sometimes, it may be useful to look at [the full documentation for KeyEvent](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/awt/event/KeyEvent.html) as well. The part of interest will probably be the "Method Summary", which describes what methods are available to be called (try ctrl + f for "Method Summary").
